CROSS JOIN in SQL

CROSS JOIN is used to retrieve the Cartesian product of two tables, meaning every row from the first table is combined with every row from the second table.

Unlike other joins, CROSS JOIN does not require a matching condition (ON clause).

Syntax

SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table1
CROSS JOIN table2;


Example

Employee Table

| emp_id | emp_name |
| ------ | -------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   |
| 2      | Rahul    |
| 3      | Amit     |

Department Table

| dept_id | dept_name |
| ------- | --------- |
| 101     | IT        |
| 102     | HR        |

Query

SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_id,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
CROSS JOIN Department d;


Output

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_id | dept_name |
| ------ | -------- | ------- | --------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | 101     | IT        |
| 1      | Hitesh   | 102     | HR        |
| 2      | Rahul    | 101     | IT        |
| 2      | Rahul    | 102     | HR        |
| 3      | Amit     | 101     | IT        |
| 3      | Amit     | 102     | HR        |

Explanation:

- The Employee table has 3 rows.
- The Department table has 2 rows.
- The result contains 3 × 2 = 6 rows, where each employee is paired with every department.

Formula
Total Rows = Rows in Table1 × Rows in Table2


For the above example:
3 Employees × 2 Departments = 6 Records


 Note:

 - CROSS JOIN does not use an ON condition.
 - It is commonly used to generate all possible combinations of records.
 - Be cautious when joining large tables, as the result size can grow very quickly.

 Use Cases

- Generating all possible product-color combinations
- Creating calendar/date combinations
- Test data generation
- Producing all possible permutations between two datasets
